Step-by-Step Approach
Add a Custom Maven Plugin to Run Python Tests:

We’ll use the exec-maven-plugin in the pom.xml to execute Python tests as part of the Maven lifecycle.
Modify the Jenkinsfile:

Ensure the Jenkinsfile has the necessary stages to execute both the Maven build and Python tests.

Add the following configuration to your pom.xml under the <build> section, within <plugins>:

<plugin>
    <groupId>org.codehaus.mojo</groupId>
    <artifactId>exec-maven-plugin</artifactId>
    <version>3.0.0</version>
    <executions>
        <execution>
            <id>run-python-tests</id>
            <phase>test</phase> <!-- This will bind the execution to the test phase -->
            <goals>
                <goal>exec</goal>
            </goals>
            <configuration>
                <executable>sh</executable>
                <arguments>
                    <argument>-c</argument>
                    <argument>
                        source venv/bin/activate &amp;&amp; pytest unittests/ --junitxml=report.xml
                    </argument>
                </arguments>
            </configuration>
        </execution>
    </executions>
</plugin>





Explanation:
Plugin Details:
exec-maven-plugin: Allows running any external process from Maven.
Execution:
Binds to the Maven test phase to ensure Python tests run after Java unit tests.
Activates the virtual environment and runs pytest on the unittests/ directory.
Generates a report.xml file for test results.
Step 2: Modify the Jenkinsfile
You’ll need to update the Jenkinsfile to ensure the Python virtual environment is set up before running the tests.


pipeline {
    agent any

    stages {
        stage('Build and Test') {
            steps {
                script {
                    try {
                        // Build the Java project using Maven
                        sh 'mvn clean install'

                        // Run Python tests as part of Maven build
                        sh '''
                        python3.11 -m venv venv
                        source venv/bin/activate
                        pip install --upgrade pip
                        pip install -r requirements.txt
                        mvn test
                        '''
                    } catch (Exception e) {
                        echo "Build failed with error: ${e.message}"
                        currentBuild.result = 'FAILURE'
                        throw e
                    }
                }
            }
        }
    }

    post {
        always {
            archiveArtifacts artifacts: '**/target/*.jar', allowEmptyArchive: true
            junit '**/report.xml' // This will pick up the Python test report
        }
    }
}



Explanation:
Python Environment Setup:

Creates and activates a virtual environment for Python.
Installs dependencies from requirements.txt.
Maven Build:

mvn clean install will build the Java project and run tests, including Python tests because we integrated it into the pom.xml.
Post Actions:

archiveArtifacts: Archives the Java build artifacts.
junit '**/report.xml': Archives the Python test results.
Step 3: Integration in Jenkins
Commit Changes:

Add the modified pom.xml and Jenkinsfile to your repository.
Push the changes to the appropriate branch.
Configure Jenkins Job:

Ensure the Jenkins job is linked to the correct branch.
The Jenkins pipeline should now include both Java and Python tests as part of the build.
Run the Jenkins Job:

Trigger the Jenkins job and monitor the console output.
You should see both the Maven build and Python tests being executed.


